  "exemplar_id": "ex_peds_travel_contact_001",
  "frozen": true,
  "context_summary": "2.5-month-old infant brought to the ED by parents with two days of cough, fever above 38°C (rectal), tachypnea, and now requiring 2L supplemental oxygen. He has yellow sputum, decreased wet diapers, poor feeding, and is inconsolably fussy. He had a similar episode last month diagnosed as bronchiolitis/viral URI requiring two-day hospitalization. His birth and developmental history are unremarkable and immunizations are up to date. The doctor has just asked whether anyone around the family has been sick and the parent has said no.",
  "good_next_question": "Any travel recently?",
  "rationale": "When the standard sick-contact question returns negative, this follow-up question is what surfaces the case-defining exposure — the parent volunteers that grandma traveled to Mexico recently and spent the day with the infant the week prior. In a febrile infant under three months requiring oxygen, the differential is wide (bacterial sepsis, RSV, pertussis, COVID, influenza, atypical pneumonia, and travel-related pathogens including TB or imported viral illness), and the workup is aggressive by protocol. Surfacing a Mexico travel contact in the past week meaningfully shifts the differential toward considering pertussis (regional outbreaks), tuberculosis exposure, measles in an unvaccinated-age infant, and influenza strains the infant could have been exposed to through an adult carrier. The lesson this exemplar encodes is that 'sick contacts' for an infant must extend beyond the immediate household — caregivers, grandparents, and anyone with recent travel are all relevant vectors, and parents often interpret 'sick contacts' narrowly. Asking the travel question separately (rather than accepting the 'no one is sick' answer) is what catches the exposure that changes empiric coverage and isolation decisions.",
  "tags": [
    "pediatric",
    "infant",
    "infectious",
    "respiratory",
    "fever",
    "risk_factor_probe",
    "travel_history"
  ],
